She has described how the process of decision making was operated in Somerset during the relevant period.  Dates for specific decisions for individual children were timetabled in parallel with the timetable determined by the Family Court in respect of the filing of evidence and listing of final hearing.  It was part of her function to book the case in Ms Winter’s diary for decision making.  A detailed spreadsheet was maintained listing the name of the child together with the social worker’s name, the date when final evidence was due to be filed with the court, dates when various paperwork was due and, finally, the outcome of the decision for that child.  It was part of Ms Poore’s function to review all the child permanence reports prepared by the relevant social worker.  For the purposes of the agency decision maker’s review of the case, four packs of papers were prepared, two of which were provided to Dr Smith and Ms Winter (or whichever agency decision maker was tasked with making decisions for any particular child

